## Library-First Principle
- Before implementing yourself, first ask "is there a library for this?"
- Actively leverage existing libraries; minimize custom implementations
- Before adding a new package: 1) check official docs for the latest stable version, 2) verify it can't be replaced by an existing library

## Dependency Management
- Do not add external packages if stdlib is sufficient
- When adding: specify minimum version (e.g., `>=2.0`); the lockfile handles exact version pinning
- After adding: update related docs (README, library mapping, etc.)
- Security: make it a habit to check for vulnerabilities (`pip-audit`, `npm audit`, etc.)

## Research Principles
- Always check official documentation before working with new libraries, tech decisions, security code, or error resolution
- Work based on latest information, not training data (prevent use of deprecated APIs)
- Priority: official docs > web search > GitHub code search
- Cache research results to avoid repetition
- Record findings based on official docs or external research in `docs/research-notes.md` or `docs/decisions.md` with source and verification date

## Preflight Principles
- Do not jump straight into writing code
- First: assess the current state (what's done and what's not)
- Next: establish a concrete execution plan (what, in what order, how)
- Then: confirm the plan before executing
- Leave the plan as a log so "why we proceeded this way" is traceable

## Educational Progress Principles
- Leave short comments at structural boundaries that need explanation
- Comments should focus only on "why it's split this way" and "where this value is used"
- Comments that merely restate the code are forbidden
- When adding a new module, briefly note the key design rationale

## AI Integration
- All AI calls must go through an abstract interface (direct API calls forbidden)

## Error Handling Rules
- All external calls (AI API, DB, Redis, Git) must be wrapped in try/except, catching only specific exceptions
- `except Exception` is allowed only at top-level entry points
- Use structured logging -- no direct use of print/logging
- Distinguish between retryable errors (transient) and non-retryable errors (permanent)

## Environment Variable Rules
- Load all environment variables in a type-safe manner (pydantic-settings, etc.)
- Secrets (API keys, etc.) must be stored only in `.env`; hardcoding in code is forbidden
- If required environment variables are missing, fail at startup with a clear error
- Document required environment variables via `.env.example`

## Safety Guards
- Do not retry more than 2 times with the same error pattern -- stop + notify user
- Immediately block circular dependencies (infinite loops like A->B->A)
- Set an AI cost budget; warn at 80%, stop at 100%
- On failure, roll back to the last safe point (git commit)
- On cascading failures, roll back to a broader scope

## Cross-Verification Principles
- AI-generated documents/outputs must be verified against actual code/state
- Spec documents vs actual code (confirm classes/methods exist)
- Progress/reports vs actual state (DB, git diff)
- Semantic verification must be done by a different call than the generating AI (no self-verification)
- On mismatch: error -> block progress, warning -> auto-correct, info -> log

## Gap Detection Principles
- After establishing a work plan, check "is anything missing?"
- Implicit Requirements: things the user didn't specify but are obviously needed (e.g., refresh tokens for auth API, brute force prevention)
- "What If" analysis: attack your own plan's blind spots
- Scope explosion prevention: maximum 5 suggestions, within 20% of original scope
- Severity classification: must_have (auto-include), should_have (suggest), nice_to_have (log only)

## Code-Documentation Sync Principles
- If you changed code, you must also update related documentation
- Selectively update only the specs/docs of affected modules (don't rewrite everything each time)
- Track change history based on git diff
- If a progress document (PROGRESS.md, etc.) exists, always keep it up to date

## Terminology Confusion Prevention
- If the same term is used in multiple contexts, always clarify the distinction
- Always make clear which context is meant in code/docs (e.g., "dev environment MCP" vs "product MCP server")
- When using an abbreviation for the first time, include the full name

## Decision Records
- Record technical decisions in `docs/decisions.md`
- Record research notes and source summaries in `docs/research-notes.md`
- Link research items as `R-xxx` and decision items as `D-xxx`
- Record not just "what" was chosen but "why", and what the alternatives were
- Compare at least 2 candidates and document the rationale
- Be more careful with irreversible decisions; move quickly with reversible ones

